1.  Introduction:

NZ-COM,  like  its  predecessor Z-Com, will  allow  the  user  to ç
install  Z-System on his CP/M 2.2 system  automatically,  without ç
any  programming or assembly.  You will have it running  on  your ç
computer in seconds.  This is where the similarity ends.  

NZ-COM  will  allow  you  to  customize  your  operating   system ç
environment  in ways you could have only dreamed about.  You  can ç
change  operating  systems at any time, even in the middle  of  a ç
multiple  command line.  You can do it manually from the  command ç
line  or automatically from within alias or menu command  scripts ç
using flow controls depending on system conditions.  

You can change the whole operating system or any part of it.  You ç
can switch from one command processor to another or from one  DOS ç
to another with a simple command.

Need more memory temporarily for a specific application?   Simply ç
load  a new system without IOP or RCP and FCP if not needed,  run ç
the  memory  hungry application (PerfectCalc comes to  mind)  and ç
when you're finished, load up your normal system again.  All this ç
is done in seconds with one multiple command.

Using NZ-COM is really simplicity itself.  You don't need  source ç
code.   You don't have to assemble or link anything.   You  don't ç
even need SYSGEN or DDT to get NZ-COM running.  You don't have to ç
'hack' on anything (unless you really want to).  

If  you  have a floppy system, copy the distribution files  to  a ç
work disk at put the distribution disk away.  If you have a  hard ç
disk system, I suggest you copy these files to the A0:  partition ç
of  the hard disk.  NZ-COM will work from any drive and user  but ç
A0: is preferred and will speed things up considerably.


Getting  NZ-COM  running  the first time is  a  two-step  process ç
almost too easy to talk about.  First use MKZCM.COM to define the ç
system  you  want to build and then use NZCOM.COM  to  build  it.  ç
Here's how:

     A>MKZCM NZCOM<cr>

MKZCM  will present a full screen describing a  full-up  Z-System ç
for your computer.  For the sake of argument, let's say you  like ç
it like that.  Press 'S' for save and MKZCM will create two files ç
for you, NZCOM.ZCM and NZCOM.ENV.  Second step:

     A>NZCOM<cr>

In  about  three shakes of the old lamb's tail, NZCOM  will  have ç
loaded  seven or so modules, written two files and given you  the ç
Z-System  A0:BASE>  prompt.   You are now in  the  world  of  the ç
living.   You have a fully functional full-featured  Z-System  at ç
your disposal.  You have arrived!

One  of  the  primary  features  of  Z-System  is  the   TERMinal ç
CAPabilities  (TERMCAP or TCAP) segment in the  environment.   As ç
delivered,  NZCOM  installs a minimum Lear-Siegler  ADM-3A  tcap.  ç
This  will suffice for most Osborne and Kaypro computers and  for ç
most  Televideo  and  Wyse terminals and many  others.   If  your ç
terminal doesn't like ADM stuff or has more capability, now is  a ç
good time to create your own NZCOM.Z3T file.  Use TCSELECT  NZCOM ç
and choose your computer or terminal from the list.  You can load ç
the resulting descriptor with NZCOM NZCOM.Z3T (or of course  with ç
LDR or JetLDR).  

NZ-COM  is  delivered with a minimal  NZCOM.NDR  Named  Directory ç
module  naming  A0:BASE  and  A15:ROOT.   This  file  is   loaded ç
automatically by NZCOM whenever there is space available for  it.  ç
You  may use MKDIR NZCOM.NDR to modify this file to taste  or  to ç
make new ones.  

2.  Practice:

Now  that we know we have Z-System, let's play around  a  little.  ç
Type MKZCM<cr> again and get the system environment map  display.  ç
You  will note that each of the segments have an address as  well ç
as  a  definite  size.  MKZCM calculates  the  addresses  of  the ç
segments  based on the CBIOS address (where your computer's  BIOS ç
really starts) and the sizes of the various segments.  The  order ç
of  the segments is fixed by MKZCM but their sizes are  definable ç
by  you.   You may lengthen, shorten or  eliminate  a  particular ç
segment by defining its size.

Let's  define  a really small (large TPA) system.  Note  the  TPA ç
size report near the bottom of the screen.  We need CCP, DOS  and ç
BIO segments as they are for the present.  Leave them alone.  The ç
IOP  (12 records) is the first candidate for  elimination.   Type ç
'4'.  Now type '0' and return.  The new display will show no  IOP ç

and a TPA 1.5k larger.  Continue with selections 5, 6, and 7  for ç
RCP,  FCP and NDR and notice how the addresses and the  TPA  size ç
change.  Due to a technicality which requires our BIO segment  on ç
a  page  rather than record boundary, you will not  gain  TPA  by ç
eliminating the SHS Shell Stack segment.  Leave it at 4 x 32.

Now type 'S'.  You will be asked for a filename. Type 'SMALL' and ç
return.  MKZCM will create SMALL.ZCM and SMALL.ENV in the current ç
directory.  Now type NZCOM SMALL.ZCM and return.  Voila, mesdames ç
et  messieurs,  the Minimum Z-System.  You will note  (run  MKZCM ç
again) that the difference of the real CBIOS address and our  NZ-ç
COM Bios address is 400h or only 1k.  That is the total  overhead ç
of  Z-System.   Whithin  1k you get  multiple  commands,  the  Z3 ç
messages,  external Path and FCB, the Wheel, the  Z3  environment ç
and termcap as well as a full 4-entry shell stack.  Still a full-ç
capability Z-System and only 1k larger than your old CP/M system.  ç
Magic.  You return to the full-up system with NZCOM<cr>.

3.  What's Going On Here?

NZ-COM  (and Z3PLUS*) is a little more than just cute.  It  is  a ç
true advance of the art.  Operating systems and segments  thereof ç
have,  until now, been 'black' magic.  The OS was just  something ç
you  learned  to live with.  From the largest mainframes  to  the ç
most modest micros, users had to simply take what the got and  do ç
the  best they could with it.  No more.  The New Z-System puts  a ç
definite  end  to  that.   The User, not  just  HAL  or  BigSoft, ç
determines his own operating system environment.  The User is not ç
stuck, either, with his last best choice.  Any part of NZ-COM can ç
be  modified  in many ways and at any time by the User  from  the ç
command  line  or  from alias or menu command  script.   The  New ç
World.

NZ-COM  consists  of  two  Major  command  files,  MKZCM.COM  and ç
NZCOM.COM, a selection of Z-system ReLocatable (ZRL) files and  a ç
number  of  utility command files.  We have  already  touched  on ç
MKZCM  and NZCOM.  The ZRL files contain the building  blocks  of ç
the system.  There are six of them contained in NZCOM.LBR:

NZCPR.ZRL      This is Jay Sage's ZCPR34 Command Processor

NZDOS.ZRL      This is Dennis Wright's ZRDOS at version 1.9c

NZBIO.ZRL      Mini-BIOS for warm-boot of NZ-COM (2 records)

NZIOP.ZRL      Dummy IOP structure

NZRCP.ZRL      The Resident Command Processor

NZFCP.ZRL      The Flow Control Processorç
ZRL files are actually REL files which can be produced by many of ç
our  favorite assemblers.  They are renamed to ZRL to  avoid  the ç
temptation  to run a standard linker on them.  These files use  a ç
multiple  Named  COMMON  Block construct which  a  normal  linker ç

simply  can't  handle.   Only NZCOM, Z3PLUS or  JetLDR  have  any ç
chance at these files.

NZ-COM uses a data structure known as an environment  descriptor, ç
Z3ENV  to  the initiated, for its operation.  Z3ENV  contains  or ç
implies the addresses and sizes of all Z-System segments as  well ç
as  other data used by the command processor and Z3 utilities  to ç
determine  or  change  system status.  Z3ENV  fully  describes  a ç
particular system for NZ-COM.  

The  output  files  from MKZCM (name.ZCM or  name.ENV)  define  a ç
complete  and  explicit  system  in  terms  of  the   environment ç
descriptor.   NZCOM can read either of these files and  determine ç
how (or whether) to make any changes to the current system.   You ç
will note that .ZCM files are actually ASCII text in the form  of ç
a standard symbol table.  You might edit this file to fine-tune a ç
system more to your liking.

The  actual programs contained in the .ZRL modules use Z3ENV  for ç
all inter-module references.  In this way a newly loaded RCP  can ç
find  the address of the command processor and other segments  of ç
interest.

NZCON.Z3T and NZCOM.NDR are binary segments which are not address ç
sensitive.  They can be loaded anywhere.  If you already have Z3T ç
and  NDR files for your current Z3 system, you may simply  rename ç
them for use under NZ-COM.  

4.  What's REALLY Going on Here?

Once  you play around a little and get used to what goes on,  you ç
will  notice NZCOM searches an LBR for its files unless told  not ç
to.   You may put any of these files into NZCOM.LBR or any  other ç
LBR  and  get them from there.  Although it costs  one  directory ç
search  to open an LBR, subsequent accesses of the LBR do not  go ç
the  the  directory  and  are,  therefore,  quick.   If  you  get ç
conscientious,  you  can  place the ZCM (or  ENV)  files  in  the ç
library   and   eliminate  that  search.   If  you   get   really ç
conscientious  and  ensure that the LBR occupies  contiguous  (or ç
contemuous) allocation blocks on your disk, it flies.

For you 'speed at any cost' types, NZCOM will build your favorite ç
system an create a single ZCI image file of it (name.ZCI).   This ç
system  can  be  loaded  in the  twinkling  of  an  eye,  without ç
reference  to  even the LBR.  No free lunch.  Each of  these  ZCI ç
files are 10 or 12 k long, costing disk space.

NZCOM  is  also  a hot package loader.  It can load  any  of  the ç
system modules individually or in groups.  As mentioned  earlier, ç
NZCOM  looks for its packages in an LBR file unless you  tell  it ç
otherwise.  You tell it 'otherwise' with an explicit DU: or  DIR: ç
reference.  Consider the possibilities.

     NZCOM NZRCP.ZRL


NZCOM  will open NZCOM.LBR, read and load NZRCP.ZRL from  it.  If ç
you want to load a file from disk, without reference to the  LBR, ç
the command might be:

     NZCOM A6:NZRCP.ZRL  or  NZCOM WORK:NZRCP.ZRL

NZCOM  supports DU: references under CP/M and either DU: or  DIR: ç
references under NZ-COM.

Let's  get really fancy and consider that we have a seperate  LBR ç
for  descriptors, NZCOM.LBR for the modules and some loose  files ç
on the disk.  We can build a system this way.

     NZCOM B0:DESC.LBR, TEST.ZCM, A0:NEWRCP.ZRL, A15:NZCOM.LBR

This will get TEST.ZCM from B0:DESC.LBR, get NEWRCP.ZRL as a disk ç
file  from  A0: and then open A15:NZCOM.LBR for the rest  of  the ç
modules required for the new system.

